20:52.919 --> 20:58.133
âª But now I'm found âª

20:58.216 --> 21:02.887
âª Was blind, but now âª

21:02.971 --> 21:07.559
âª I see âª

21:09.185 --> 21:10.645
Amen.

21:10.729 --> 21:13.773
The altar is now open
for anyone to receive Jesus.

21:17.777 --> 21:21.990
Dear God, long time no see.

21:22.073 --> 21:23.700
Um, I guess you know
how desperate I am

21:23.783 --> 21:24.909
just by me being here.

21:24.993 --> 21:27.746
But I'm willing to try
anything at this point.

21:27.829 --> 21:31.041
Please, please, I beg of you--

21:31.124 --> 21:33.251
You didn't call me back
last night.

21:33.335 --> 21:36.087
Too busy for your mama,
but you have time for this?

21:36.171 --> 21:37.881
I'm dubious, to say the least.

21:37.964 --> 21:39.799
Are you actually mad
that I'm praying?

21:39.883 --> 21:41.384
Mad?
Not mad.

21:41.468 --> 21:42.427
More confused.

21:42.510 --> 21:44.346
Suspicious.
What did you do?

21:44.429 --> 21:46.431
What trouble
did you get yourself into?

21:47.390 --> 21:51.186
I--I needed inspiration
for a new show.

21:51.269 --> 21:52.479
I thought he could help.

21:52.562 --> 21:54.773
That is a waste of his time.

21:54.856 --> 21:57.984
Can we discuss this later?

21:58.068 --> 21:59.194
I'll see you
in the lobby,

21:59.277 --> 22:02.030
at which point we'll discuss
proper kneeling attire.

22:02.113 --> 22:03.281
Mother!

22:13.875 --> 22:17.337
I have missed this place.

22:17.420 --> 22:19.923
Oh!

22:20.006 --> 22:21.716
- Mmm.
- Ooh, la, la.

22:21.800 --> 22:22.842
Oh, fantastic.

22:22.926 --> 22:24.135
Oh! Oh!

22:26.054 --> 22:28.390
A toast to us.

22:36.856 --> 22:38.191
They were just shellfish!

22:43.738 --> 22:45.573
I wish you could have seen her.

22:45.657 --> 22:47.617
Le Cordon Bleu,
the great Bugnard,

22:47.701 --> 22:49.327
all in service of her vision.

22:49.411 --> 22:51.079
Well, Bocuse's vision.

22:51.162 --> 22:55.750
But still, the fish
was lighter than a feather,

22:55.834 --> 22:57.585
which I cannot
say for this duck.

22:57.669 --> 22:58.878
It's marvelous.

22:58.962 --> 23:01.172
We haven't indulged like this
since you two left.

23:01.256 --> 23:02.382
Has it been that dreary?

23:02.465 --> 23:04.634
The man who replaced you,
George Drummond--

23:04.718 --> 23:05.677
a nincompoop.

23:05.760 --> 23:07.929
Oh, now, I liked George.

23:08.013 --> 23:10.640
He was a plodder,
playing checkers to your chess.

23:10.724 --> 23:13.101
Oh, I do miss
the challenge of it.

23:13.184 --> 23:14.936
And he did not
understand French.

23:15.020 --> 23:16.312
- Oh.
- Well,

23:16.396 --> 23:19.607
I always prided myself on that.

23:19.691 --> 23:22.569
- Wow.
- Mmm.

23:22.652 --> 23:25.947
They were, I think it is fair
to say, anni mirabiles.

23:26.031 --> 23:27.282
Oh, tout a fait.

23:27.365 --> 23:28.700
The Marshall Plan.

23:28.783 --> 23:32.162
All across Europe, would there
be democracy without it?

23:32.245 --> 23:33.329
No.

23:33.413 --> 23:34.789
Here in Paris,
the work we did

23:34.873 --> 23:36.332
with the Joint
Distribution Committee

23:36.416 --> 23:39.669
for the Jews
resettling in France--

23:39.753 --> 23:42.005
returning their homes,
their businesses,

23:42.088 --> 23:46.551
their possessions, the things
they left behind in exile.

23:46.634 --> 23:49.929
I remember them all,
every face.

23:50.013 --> 23:51.514
The Rosenthals,

23:51.598 --> 23:53.600
the Wiets,
the Blochs,

23:53.683 --> 23:55.935
the Levis,
the Steiners.

23:56.019 --> 23:59.564
They became friends of ours--
uh, some of them.

23:59.647 --> 24:02.192
We gave them back their lives.

24:02.275 --> 24:03.234
Huh.

24:04.694 --> 24:06.112
And what does that mean?

24:06.196 --> 24:07.989
You know France
less well than you think.

24:08.073 --> 24:09.949
- Annette.
- No.

24:10.033 --> 24:12.160
What's the point of this?

24:12.243 --> 24:14.871
It means we do not
change the world,

24:14.954 --> 24:17.248
only who does the hurting.

24:17.332 --> 24:19.959
Leave it
as you remember, Paul.

24:20.043 --> 24:21.002
What does it matter?

24:21.086 --> 24:21.920
It matters.

24:23.588 --> 24:25.090
It was his life's work.

24:27.008 --> 24:28.510
Florent?

24:32.097 --> 24:33.556
Turns out, we--

24:33.640 --> 24:35.809
we didn't do half the things
we thought we did.

24:35.892 --> 24:37.519
No, you did them.

24:37.602 --> 24:40.897
It just didn't change anything.

24:40.980 --> 24:43.650
France doesn't change.

24:43.733 --> 24:46.361
Paul Child
or George Drummond, so what?

24:48.196 --> 24:50.865
We are who we are who we are.

25:08.466 --> 25:11.594
You are so comfortable
in your skin.

25:11.678 --> 25:13.638
Not always.

25:13.722 --> 25:15.765
But always when I move.

25:21.479 --> 25:24.441
Life is
full of amazing things.

25:26.943 --> 25:28.987
They are not all the same.

25:29.070 --> 25:31.823
You should be open
to all of them.

25:46.296 --> 25:48.715
You couldn't sleep?

25:48.798 --> 25:51.134
No.

25:51.217 --> 25:54.220
Well, we had a lot to drink.

25:54.304 --> 25:55.347
All four of us.

25:59.100 --> 26:01.311
We know what we did.

26:01.394 --> 26:03.688
I know what you did.

26:03.772 --> 26:05.482
The Rosenthals, for one.

26:05.565 --> 26:07.317
I know what we did for them.

26:07.400 --> 26:10.111
That Rembrandt.

26:10.195 --> 26:13.073
You know, Rosa was
the one with the eye.

26:14.866 --> 26:16.785
Yeah, but he was the one
with the money.

26:20.955 --> 26:22.457
It's been such
a wonderful trip

26:22.540 --> 26:24.626
in every other way.

26:24.709 --> 26:29.005
And we still have eight hours
until the plane takes off.

26:29.089 --> 26:30.006
Let's find them.

26:32.425 --> 26:33.927
I miss them now.

26:44.979 --> 26:46.606
Ugh!

27:03.039 --> 27:05.625
Evan Jones, please.

27:05.709 --> 27:07.502
The United States.

27:07.585 --> 27:10.422
That's Beekman 64541.

27:14.509 --> 27:15.677
Evan.

27:18.096 --> 27:19.639
No, I'm fine.

27:22.017 --> 27:24.644
I missed my flight.

27:24.728 --> 27:26.229
Is that okay?

27:33.278 --> 27:35.530
Oh!
Ow.

27:37.991 --> 27:39.117
What?

27:52.797 --> 27:54.049
Huh?

27:59.095 --> 28:02.265
Ow.
Oh.

28:02.349 --> 28:03.933
This isn't dangerous, Russ?

28:04.017 --> 28:05.894
They're
peaceful protests, Marian.

28:05.977 --> 28:07.354
And I'm just filming them.

28:07.437 --> 28:08.980
Yes, but socialists.

28:09.064 --> 28:11.399
Against the war,
not the government.

28:11.483 --> 28:12.942
And this is
the United States of America.

28:13.026 --> 28:14.611
You're allowed to say
what you think.

28:14.694 --> 28:16.154
Okay.

28:16.237 --> 28:18.365
They marched
to the statehouse yesterday,

28:18.448 --> 28:20.033
and I filmed it all.

28:20.116 --> 28:21.951
Some students, mostly.
Some retirees.

28:22.035 --> 28:24.245
Oh, I even interviewed
a housewife like you.

28:24.329 --> 28:25.413
How open-minded.

28:25.497 --> 28:26.831
Television is
the key, Marian.

28:26.915 --> 28:29.042
I can connect people
all across the country.

28:29.125 --> 28:31.336
Instead of 100 small protests,

28:31.419 --> 28:32.962
now they're part of a movement.

28:34.005 --> 28:34.923
Oh.

28:35.006 --> 28:36.383
Oh.
No, no, no.

28:36.466 --> 28:37.425
That's right.

28:37.509 --> 28:38.426
Make noise.

28:38.510 --> 28:40.011
Make noise, little Vicky.

28:40.095 --> 28:42.305
Your daddy's gonna change
the world.

28:42.389 --> 28:44.182
After that, maybe
a few diapers.

28:44.265 --> 28:45.600
You bet.

28:50.021 --> 28:52.065
This is something
you two cooked up?

28:52.148 --> 28:54.901
Look, if I had wanted
to expand my repertoire

28:54.984 --> 28:56.695
to include the subgenre

28:56.778 --> 28:59.406
of lightly pornographic
self-help literature,

28:59.489 --> 29:00.990
I would have let you know.

29:01.074 --> 29:02.575
I'm sorry, Albert,
but the author

29:02.659 --> 29:05.078
of "Birdwatching:
An Ornithological Diary

29:05.161 --> 29:07.038
in 30 Species" had to cancel.

29:07.122 --> 29:09.249
Let me guess.
Bad clams again?

29:09.332 --> 29:12.002
Well, last time it was--
it was Updike.

29:12.085 --> 29:13.003
And that worked out well.

29:13.086 --> 29:14.754
Surely even you
and Ms. Levitch

29:14.838 --> 29:16.673
can see the difference
between John Updike

29:16.756 --> 29:18.758
and--and Helen Gurley Brown.

29:18.842 --> 29:20.760
Oh, that can't be
her real name.

29:20.844 --> 29:23.388
Albert, as a new
and now die-hard fan

29:23.471 --> 29:24.973
of the show myself,
I'm just trying

29:25.056 --> 29:26.349
to entice a new audience.

29:26.433 --> 29:27.767
Well, what will it be
next, Levitch?

29:27.851 --> 29:29.477
I strip to my skivvies
and juggle?

29:31.271 --> 29:34.357
How am I gonna get
that visual out of my head?

29:34.441 --> 29:38.820
Now, uh, what I found tit--
titillating about your book--

29:38.903 --> 29:40.321
Why Albert, you pussycat.

29:40.405 --> 29:41.948
What did you find titillating?

29:43.491 --> 29:47.871
Uh, your focus
on financial independence.

29:47.954 --> 29:50.165
I hadn't thought
of it that way.

29:50.248 --> 29:53.543
That's--
well, that's not so terrible.

29:53.626 --> 29:55.920
Rather big of you to say.

29:56.004 --> 29:56.921
Big of me?

29:57.005 --> 29:58.715
Very big.

29:58.798 --> 30:01.384
Financial independence
and sexual freedom

30:01.468 --> 30:03.345
are inextricably intertwined.

30:03.428 --> 30:05.347
I was 37 when I got married,

30:05.430 --> 30:06.556
but you don't honestly believe

30:06.639 --> 30:08.641
I was a virgin at 37?

30:10.060 --> 30:11.353
I guess I don't.

30:11.436 --> 30:13.438
So isn't that
the truth of it?

30:13.521 --> 30:15.607
Well, young lady,
you know what they say.

30:15.690 --> 30:17.400
Good girls go to heaven.

30:17.484 --> 30:21.321
True.
But bad girls go everywhere.

30:21.404 --> 30:23.740
From the age of 20--
what the hell, 19--

30:23.823 --> 30:25.992
I explored my options sexually

30:26.076 --> 30:27.786
until I met the right partner.

30:27.869 --> 30:30.038
I had my fill
of all shapes and sizes.

30:30.121 --> 30:31.289
Good God.

30:31.373 --> 30:33.291
Having my own income allowed

30:33.375 --> 30:35.043
for some adventurous
discernment.

30:35.126 --> 30:36.711
The gift of time.

30:36.795 --> 30:38.171
Did your wife have a chance

30:38.254 --> 30:40.965
to explore
her options sexually?

30:41.049 --> 30:42.842
Well--

30:42.926 --> 30:44.094
I bet she did.

30:44.177 --> 30:45.470
She just didn't tell you.

30:45.553 --> 30:48.014
Now, it's not
your fault, professor.

30:48.098 --> 30:49.307
It's societal.

30:49.391 --> 30:51.726
And that's what my book,
and now the movie,

30:51.810 --> 30:53.895
are here to dismantle.

30:53.978 --> 30:55.480
You know, in my day,

30:55.563 --> 30:57.816
we read books
like "Anna Karenina"

30:57.899 --> 30:59.359
and "The Scarlet Letter,"

30:59.442 --> 31:02.904
and women were punished
for their sexuality.

31:04.531 --> 31:07.784
Your day has passed, old man.

31:12.664 --> 31:13.623
I have to pee.

31:15.750 --> 31:19.379
This was one of my favorite
apartments in all of Paris,

31:19.462 --> 31:21.423
and my very favorite couple.

31:21.506 --> 31:22.674
Yes.

31:26.261 --> 31:27.804
Bonjour.

31:27.887 --> 31:29.431
Uh, bonjour, mademoiselle.

31:55.123 --> 31:56.583
- Au revoir.
- Au revoir.

31:56.666 --> 31:58.209
Au revoir.

32:01.087 --> 32:01.921
Hmm.

32:30.825 --> 32:31.951
Merci.

33:20.041 --> 33:22.002
In the long dark tunnel
of night

33:22.085 --> 33:23.336
that is human existence,

33:23.420 --> 33:25.422
last night was a revelation.

33:25.505 --> 33:27.173
You mean you had a good time.

33:27.257 --> 33:29.217
I'll still never put
pen to paper again.

33:29.300 --> 33:30.844
That's useless folly.

33:30.927 --> 33:35.098
But from now on, I shall dance
whenever I can.

33:37.058 --> 33:42.939
When I got home, Simone
was so worried and jealous.

33:43.023 --> 33:45.608
Who stays out
till 3:00 a.m. at my age?

33:47.485 --> 33:49.404
We never went to sleep at all.

33:49.487 --> 33:53.867
Oh.
Well, glad I could help.

33:53.950 --> 33:56.536
Simone wants to meet you.

33:56.619 --> 33:59.497
This woman who can bring
people back from the dead.

33:59.581 --> 34:01.291
Will you join us?

34:01.374 --> 34:02.834
For lunch, dinner?

34:02.917 --> 34:07.255
Oh...
there can be dinner too.

34:08.882 --> 34:10.091
Oh.

34:10.175 --> 34:11.051
Oh!

34:14.721 --> 34:16.764
Oh, really, JP.

34:20.893 --> 34:22.645
I'm seeing someone.

34:27.150 --> 34:29.319
I still know my way
around the Paris bureaucracy

34:29.402 --> 34:30.320
as well as any man.

34:30.402 --> 34:32.405
An address for the Rosenthals.

34:33.822 --> 34:34.699
You okay, Jule?

34:36.201 --> 34:37.869
It's from Chef Bugnard.

34:37.952 --> 34:38.786
Oh.

34:40.621 --> 34:42.623
"I was so happy
to see you today, Julia,

34:42.706 --> 34:44.333
"all these years later.

34:44.417 --> 34:46.878
"Teaching you was one
of the great joys of my life,

34:46.960 --> 34:49.422
"and now you are
my teacher, too.

34:49.505 --> 34:51.257
"But I will be happy
to miss you,

34:51.341 --> 34:54.177
"because your work
is in America now.

34:54.260 --> 34:56.096
"Do not be afraid of the new.

34:56.179 --> 35:01.351
"It does not erase the past,
only build on it.

35:01.434 --> 35:03.687
"Show the world how to cook,

35:03.770 --> 35:06.731
"daughter of Escoffier,

35:06.815 --> 35:08.733
"madame ambassadress,

35:08.817 --> 35:10.777
my shining student."

35:26.793 --> 35:27.669
Hello?

35:30.130 --> 35:32.215
Oh, Mom.

35:32.298 --> 35:33.758
What--what are you doing
with those?

35:33.842 --> 35:36.302
Did you stop
ironing your sheets?

35:36.386 --> 35:39.806
I never ironed
my sheets, Mom.

35:39.889 --> 35:42.892
You know they actually last
longer if you care for them?

35:42.976 --> 35:45.478
Did you pop over here
just to tell me that?

35:45.562 --> 35:46.771
No, I came to talk to you.

35:46.855 --> 35:49.232
The sheets called out to me
from the other room.

35:49.315 --> 35:51.401
I will try to find some time
this weekend.

35:51.484 --> 35:54.946
Unless you're in church
again, I suppose.

35:55.030 --> 35:56.406
It's possible.

35:57.991 --> 35:58.825
Alice.

36:00.452 --> 36:02.037
Alice.

36:02.120 --> 36:05.874
Even if you have no one else
to talk to, you always have me.

36:05.957 --> 36:08.418
And I answer quicker than God.

36:10.211 --> 36:12.422
Can I help you with anything?

36:12.505 --> 36:13.340
No.

36:15.050 --> 36:17.552
No.
I'm just blocked at work.

36:17.635 --> 36:19.346
Well, her fangs were out.

36:19.429 --> 36:20.930
What can I say?

36:21.014 --> 36:22.766
We should never book
New Yorkers.

36:22.849 --> 36:24.142
Is that right?

36:24.225 --> 36:26.061
You know, I admit
I didn't properly prepare

36:26.144 --> 36:27.562
the way I like to.

36:27.645 --> 36:30.523
But have you read it, Hunter?

36:30.607 --> 36:32.567
"Sex and the Single Girl"?

36:32.650 --> 36:33.651
It's trash.

36:33.735 --> 36:36.237
I don't know how to help trash.

36:36.321 --> 36:38.823
But don't you realize,
Albert?

36:38.907 --> 36:40.575
She was there to help you.

36:42.535 --> 36:43.912
How do you mean?

36:43.995 --> 36:45.789
Do you want me
to spell it out for you?

36:45.872 --> 36:48.458
I understand
that times are changing.

36:48.541 --> 36:49.834
I do.

36:49.918 --> 36:51.836
I mean, it's happening
at the college, too.

36:51.920 --> 36:55.924
I recently added Willa Cather
to my syllabus, and a Bronte.

36:56.007 --> 36:57.342
Well, that's terrific.

36:57.425 --> 36:59.344
I'm sure your students
will appreciate it,

36:59.427 --> 37:02.347
especially those
of the fairer sex.

37:02.430 --> 37:04.683
It meant losing "Moby-Dick."

37:04.766 --> 37:06.935
You can't add
without subtracting.

37:08.311 --> 37:11.815
Took the words
right out of my mouth.

37:11.898 --> 37:14.275
Albert, this is not easy.

37:14.359 --> 37:16.361
I've actually had
stomach issues for days

37:16.444 --> 37:18.905
just figuring out
how to say this to you.

37:20.240 --> 37:22.617
It's not gonna work, Albert.

37:24.369 --> 37:26.705
Okay.
Invite her back.

37:26.788 --> 37:27.956
I'll do better.

37:28.039 --> 37:30.083
I'll do better this time,
I promise.

37:30.166 --> 37:31.918
You can finish out
the season,

37:32.002 --> 37:34.170
and we'll give you
a proper sendoff.

37:36.297 --> 37:40.885
You've been a vital part
of WGBH since the beginning,

37:40.969 --> 37:43.763
and for that,
I'll always be grateful.

37:47.434 --> 37:49.602
Oh.

37:49.686 --> 37:50.979
I see.

37:52.897 --> 37:54.315
Well, then.

37:56.484 --> 37:58.403
Thank you, Hunter.

38:00.113 --> 38:02.907
I hope someone treats you
with the same grace

38:02.991 --> 38:05.493
when your time comes.

38:05.577 --> 38:07.162
And it's coming.

38:13.793 --> 38:15.628
Oh, my God,
I almost feel bad.

38:15.712 --> 38:17.630
Don't.
She wiped the floor with him.

38:17.714 --> 38:18.715
He was a mop.

38:18.798 --> 38:22.677
He was a wet, wet mop.

38:24.012 --> 38:26.264
You know, her sexual politics
are an A-plus,

38:26.348 --> 38:27.891
but her food politics--

38:27.974 --> 38:29.017
I don't know
if you read the book.

38:29.100 --> 38:30.352
They're just the worst.

38:30.435 --> 38:32.103
If she saw two women
eating dessert

38:32.187 --> 38:33.730
with nary a man present,

38:33.813 --> 38:35.190
we'd be thrown into girl jail.

38:35.273 --> 38:37.067
And it's all
a little grandiose.

38:37.150 --> 38:39.486
And true, she talks
about sexual freedom,

38:39.569 --> 38:40.820
and quite frankly at that,

38:40.904 --> 38:43.573
but without any real
nuts-and-bolts information

38:43.656 --> 38:45.075
about how
to take care of yourself

38:45.158 --> 38:46.868
within that freedom.

38:46.951 --> 38:49.037
You mean orgasms?

38:49.120 --> 38:50.163
I mean pregnancy.

38:52.832 --> 38:56.336
Okay.
I had a night.

38:56.419 --> 38:57.671
A--a great night.

38:57.754 --> 38:59.631
A really great night.

38:59.714 --> 39:00.924
Sounds like a great night.

39:01.007 --> 39:02.842
It was, but now I am afraid

39:02.926 --> 39:05.470
that it's going to cost me
the rest of my life.

39:05.553 --> 39:07.722
I'm nauseous, I have
this weird pain in my side,

39:07.806 --> 39:09.474
and I have to pee all the time.

39:09.557 --> 39:11.101
When did you have your night?

39:11.184 --> 39:12.560
It was four days ago.

39:12.644 --> 39:14.270
No, you're not pregnant.

39:14.354 --> 39:15.647
And the odds
of getting pregnant

39:15.730 --> 39:18.149
from having sex one time
are super low.

39:18.233 --> 39:21.361
It was three times.

39:21.444 --> 39:22.404
You're still not pregnant,

39:22.487 --> 39:23.863
and if you were,
you wouldn't know,

39:23.947 --> 39:25.115
not yet.

39:26.950 --> 39:29.786
Can I ask you
an intimate question?

39:29.869 --> 39:30.995
I mean, you can ask.

39:31.079 --> 39:34.416
After all those times,
did you pee?

39:34.499 --> 39:35.667
No.

39:35.750 --> 39:37.961
But we spooned.

39:38.044 --> 39:39.212
You should have peed.

39:39.295 --> 39:41.256
It's, uh, sort of a rule,
my dear.

39:41.339 --> 39:42.424
A rule?

39:42.507 --> 39:45.176
To prevent you
from getting a UTI.

39:45.260 --> 39:46.636
You have a UTI.

39:46.720 --> 39:47.846
Oh, uh--

39:47.929 --> 39:50.056
A urinary tract infection.

39:50.140 --> 39:51.224
Oh.

39:52.809 --> 39:54.394
Oh, how wonderful!

39:54.477 --> 39:55.687
Oh.

39:55.770 --> 39:57.731
Oh, thank you.

39:57.814 --> 40:00.775
So we need to get you
on some antibiotics,

40:00.859 --> 40:04.320
and then, if you want
to have sex a fourth time...

40:04.404 --> 40:05.613
Yes, I do.

40:05.697 --> 40:07.073
You need to get
on contraception.

40:07.157 --> 40:09.034
And I will help you.

40:09.117 --> 40:12.245
Well, you are amazing.

40:12.328 --> 40:14.289
You should write a book.

40:14.372 --> 40:15.582
Maybe I should.

40:15.665 --> 40:17.334
My parents would plotz.

40:17.417 --> 40:18.918
Or better yet, make a show.

40:19.002 --> 40:20.920
Women talking to women
about things

40:21.004 --> 40:22.422
no one else talks about
on television.

40:22.505 --> 40:24.632
Is this what you
wanted to spitball about?

40:24.716 --> 40:26.885
Mm-hmm.

40:26.968 --> 40:27.886
Cool.

40:27.969 --> 40:30.263
To Julia.

40:30.347 --> 40:32.349
For bringing us together.

40:32.432 --> 40:34.017
To Julia.

40:36.811 --> 40:39.189
I didn't know
my aunt and uncle well.

40:39.272 --> 40:42.150
Well, they were
wonderful people.

40:42.233 --> 40:43.485
And so charming.

40:43.568 --> 40:47.197
And they had us over one night
for Friday night dinner.

40:47.280 --> 40:48.990
And I discovered challah bread,

40:49.074 --> 40:50.617
and nothing's been
the same since.

40:51.951 --> 40:54.079
Are they no longer in Paris?

40:54.162 --> 40:55.330
They tried.

40:55.413 --> 40:57.165
That's probably
when you knew them.

40:57.248 --> 40:58.750
But it was very hard

40:58.833 --> 41:00.794
for many Jewish people
after the war.

41:00.877 --> 41:04.673
Guilt made the anti-Semitism
worse, not better.

41:04.756 --> 41:08.510
After all, Paris stands
because she gave up her Jews.

41:08.593 --> 41:12.931
We were made to feel
like thieves in our own homes.

41:13.014 --> 41:15.433
Neighbors would stare.

41:15.517 --> 41:17.894
Worse than stare.

41:17.977 --> 41:19.521
It was too much
for my aunt and uncle.

41:19.604 --> 41:22.732
They sold the flat
and moved to Israel.

41:24.234 --> 41:25.777
- Oh.
- Gosh.

41:25.860 --> 41:27.112
Yes.

41:30.657 --> 41:32.200
I'm sorry
for taking up your time

41:32.283 --> 41:33.326
and dredging all this up.

41:33.410 --> 41:34.828
No, no, no.

41:34.911 --> 41:36.871
It's nice to remember.

41:36.955 --> 41:40.458
Well, not nice, but important.

41:42.210 --> 41:43.837
My parents converted.

41:43.920 --> 41:45.130
They didn't want to leave,

41:45.213 --> 41:47.590
and that felt
like the safest way to stay.

41:47.674 --> 41:49.050
France is their home.

41:49.134 --> 41:52.053
My aunt and uncle
didn't understand.

41:52.137 --> 41:55.140
But for us, it was
the right thing.

41:55.223 --> 41:57.225
Yes, you poor soul.

42:00.812 --> 42:05.108
Your aunt and uncle had
a magnificent art collection.

42:05.191 --> 42:08.570
It was part of my job
to--to help locate it.

42:10.864 --> 42:11.823
I'm sorry.

42:15.118 --> 42:17.328
Please don't apologize.
There's...

42:17.412 --> 42:20.457
there's nothing,
uh, for you to apologize for.

42:20.540 --> 42:22.459
I just wish I had
a better answer.

42:23.877 --> 42:26.463
Yes.
I do, too.

42:33.762 --> 42:34.846
It's stunning.

42:39.267 --> 42:41.269
"Donor unknown."

42:43.146 --> 42:44.439
They've been erased.

42:53.114 --> 42:55.575
You tried, Paulski.

42:55.658 --> 42:57.369
What does it matter?

42:58.953 --> 43:01.706
It matters to me.

43:01.790 --> 43:04.250
And I'm sure
it mattered to them.

43:04.334 --> 43:06.252
They lost everything.

43:06.336 --> 43:08.046
What I lost...

43:12.133 --> 43:16.137
We just have no idea, do we?

43:16.221 --> 43:20.266
What any of it means.

43:20.350 --> 43:22.102
What we do.

43:37.534 --> 43:40.704
I sometimes wonder,

43:40.787 --> 43:43.123
if we had had children...

43:45.083 --> 43:47.460
They would have been
who they are...

43:49.713 --> 43:52.549
Not the sum
of everything we gave them.

43:56.302 --> 43:58.847
You were the one
who reminded me,

43:58.930 --> 44:02.726
we don't control
what the things we do mean,

44:02.809 --> 44:04.394
only what we want them to mean.

44:06.062 --> 44:08.356
I did, didn't I?

44:08.440 --> 44:11.067
The show is our baby.

44:11.151 --> 44:15.280
It's growing up,
and it needs us.

44:15.363 --> 44:18.825
We still have chapters
left to write, Paulski.

44:18.908 --> 44:22.328
We don't need
to look back anymore.

44:22.412 --> 44:24.539
The climax of the story

44:24.622 --> 44:29.711
always occurs
in the second act.

44:31.296 --> 44:33.340
That's the best part.
